  "issue_title": "[BUG] repo_weight rounded to 2 decimals discards up to 14% of the JSON precision",
  "issue_body": "## Description\n\n`calculate_pr_multipliers` (`gittensor/validator/oss_contributions/scoring.py:232`) and `_collect_issues_from_prs` (`gittensor/validator/issue_discovery/scoring.py:280`) apply `round(repo_config.weight, 2)` before assigning the repo weight as a multiplier. Weights in `master_repositories.json` are 4-decimal and most sit in `[0.03, 0.15]` \u2014 where the 2nd decimal is the most significant digit \u2014 so rounding there distorts the multiplier by up to 14% per repo and flows into `earned_score`.\n\n## Steps to Reproduce\n\n1. Run:\n   ```python\n   from gittensor.validator.utils.load_weights import load_master_repo_weights\n   repos = load_master_repo_weights()\n   w = repos['antoniorodr/cronboard'].weight  # 0.0349\n   print(w, round(w, 2))  # 0.0349 0.03 \u2014 14% loss\n   ```\n2. Trace through the multiplier chain in `calculate_pr_multipliers` \u2014 the rounded 0.03 is what reaches `earned_score`.\n\n## Expected Behavior\n\n`repo_weight_multiplier` preserves the full precision from `master_repositories.json`.\n\n## Actual Behavior\n\n75 of 214 tracked repos distort by >5%, 20 by >10%, worst case \u221214% (`antoniorodr/cronboard` 0.0349 \u2192 0.03). Two repos with nearly identical weights (`cronboard` 0.0349 vs `fzf` 0.0351) land on opposite sides of the rounding boundary, creating a 33% reward spread for identical work.\n\n## Environment\n\n- OS: Linux\n- Python version: 3.12\n- Commit/Version: `test` branch @ `bad35f7`\n\n## Additional Context\n\n`issue_multiplier`, `label_multiplier`, `review_quality_multiplier`, and `credibility_multiplier` also use `round(..., 2)`, but their values already sit at 2-decimal boundaries (1.00, 1.25, 1.50, etc.) so the loss is negligible. `repo_weight` is uniquely affected because it clusters near 0.03.\n\n**Suggested fix:** drop the `round(..., 2)` at both assignment sites so the full 4-decimal precision reaches the `earned_score` product. Display/log formatting can round independently.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-04-21T16:35:40.000Z",
